1. Income

  1. Describe in detail the features you observe in the boxplots below, plotted with data from the ex0525 dataset, Sleuth3 page. (see page 29 in Graphical Data Analysis in R for a list of features to concentrate on, and the numbered list on the bottom of page 43 for an example of how to describe features of a graph in words.) [5 points]
#install.packages("Sleuth3")
library(Sleuth3)
library(tidyverse)

# convert Educ from an integer to a factor, and make "<12" the first factor level 
mydata <- ex0525 %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(Educ = forcats::fct_relevel(Educ, "<12"))

ggplot(mydata, aes(Educ, Income2005)) +
  geom_boxplot() + 
  coord_flip()   # for horizontal boxplots

Answer: Every boxplot has the big outliers and all of them the distribution are right-skewed. Comparing with these five boxplot, we can see that: 1.The group with longer years of education have higher income than the group with shorter years if education. 2.The group with longer years of education have has more extreme outliers of income than the group with shorter years if education. 3.The group with longer years of education have has more more dispersedly distribuation of income than the group with shorter years if education.

  1. Plot a histogram of the Income2005 variable in the dataset referenced in part a). [3 points]
ggplot(mydata, aes(Income2005)) + geom_histogram(color = "black", fill = "blue", binwidth = 20000)

  1. Use +facet_wrap(~Educ) to facet the histogram on education level. [3 points]
ggplot(mydata, aes(Income2005)) + geom_histogram(color = "black", fill = "blue", binwidth = 20000) + facet_wrap(~Educ)

  1. What do you learn from the histograms that wasn’t apparent in the boxplots from question 1? [3 points] Answer: 1.comparing with those graph, the age 12 group has much more dataset.Age smaller than 12 group has smallest dataset. Other 3 gruoups have the simillary dataset.
  1. 5 groups are all uni-model.

2. Respiratory Rates

  1. Plot right closed and right open histograms for each of the two variables in the ex0824 dataset in the Sleuth3 package using default binwidths and breaks. (4 histograms in total). [4 points]
data2 <- ex0824
par(mfrow = c(2, 2), las = 1)
Histogram = hist(data2$Age, col = "blue", right = FALSE, xlab = 'Age', main = 'Histogram of Age(right open)', cex.main = 0.8)
hist(data2$Age, col = "blue", left = FALSE, xlab = 'Age', main = 'Histogram of Age(right closed)', cex.main = 0.8)
hist(data2$Rate, col = "blue", right = FALSE, xlab = 'Rate', main = 'Histogram of Rate(right open)', cex.main = 0.8)
hist(data2$Rate, col = "blue", left = FALSE, xlab = 'Rate', main = 'Histogram of Rate(right closed)', cex.main = 0.8)

  1. For which variable, Age or Rate, do the two versions differ more? Why? [3 points] Answer:

Variable Rate differ more.Because the Age is decimals,Rate are integers. The probability that Rate locates on the boundary will larger than Age.

  1. Redraw the Age histograms with different parameters so that the right closed and right open versions are identical. [3 points]
par(mfrow = c(1, 2), las = 1)
hist(data2$Age, col = "blue", breaks = Histogram$breaks - 0.1, right = FALSE, xlab = 'Age', main = 'Histogram of Age(right open)', cex.main = 0.8)
hist(data2$Age, col = "blue", breaks = Histogram$breaks - 0.1, left = FALSE, xlab = 'Age', main = 'Histogram of Age(right closed)', cex.main = 0.8)

4. Finches

  1. Plot separate density histograms of the beak depth of the finches in case0201 from the Sleuth3 package, with density curves overlaid as on page 34 of the textbook. (However, do this by facetting on Year rather than using grid.arrange). [3 points]
data4 = case0201
ggplot(data4, aes(Depth)) + geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), binwidth=1, col = 'black', fill = "lightblue") + geom_density(col = 'yellow') + facet_wrap(~Year)

  1. Plot both density curves on the same graph to facilitate comparison. Make 1976 yellow and 1978 blue. Use alpha blending so the fills are transparent. [3 points]
library(ggplot2)
library(reshape2)
x <- data.frame(Year1976 = data4$Depth[data4$Year == '1976'], Year1976 = data4$Depth[data4$Year == '1978'])
newdata <- melt(x)
ggplot(newdata,aes(value, fill=variable)) + geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), binwidth=0.1, col = 'black',fill = 'red') + geom_density(alpha=0.25) + scale_fill_manual( values = c("yellow","blue"))

  1. Based on your graphs in parts a) and b), describe how the distributions differ by year. [3 points]

Answer:

From graps in a) and b), the distributation in 1978 shif to right comparing to distributation in 1976.

5. Salary

Is the Salary variable in the case0101 of Sleuth3 normally distributed? Use two different graphical methods to provide evidence. [6 points] The first method I just used qqplots and shapiro-Wilk test.

library("ggpubr")
data5 = case0102
qqnorm(data5$Salary)
qqline(data5$Salary, col = 2)

The first method I just used qqplots to check the normal distribution.From the Q-Q plot, it is not a very good stright line. This may not a normal distributation.

ggdensity(data5$Salary, main = "Density plot of salary", xlab = "Salary")

Second I used density plot which the density plot provides a visual judgment about whether the distribution is bell shaped. From the graph it not a perfect bell shaped.

shapiro.test(data5$Salary)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  data5$Salary
## W = 0.96573, p-value = 0.0152

From the Shapiro-Wilk normality test, p-value was 0.0152 < 0.05. So we reject the null hypothesis that the salary data is normally distributed.
